Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.340 --> 00:00:03.140
Do not avert your eyes.

00:00:03.200 --> 00:00:04.700
That's what's coming at us.

00:00:04.860 --> 00:00:10.980
This is what a collective anonymous body of majority wants to see on television.

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:14.280
I think about this quote a lot from Werner Herzog.

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:17.740
He was talking about television, and specifically Wrestle Mania, but

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:21.320
I think it it applies to any form of popular entertainment.

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:24.020
The basic idea is that the most popular things,

00:00:24.100 --> 00:00:28.215
the biggest movies and TV shows and even digital media

00:00:28.215 --> 00:00:30.655
are a reflection of what we want to see,

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:35.880
so we can read from them insights about our desires and aversions.

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:40.820
As professor John Hunter from Bucknell pointed out recently in a TEDx talk, which I'll link below,

00:00:40.820 --> 00:00:44.860
our tentpole movies aren't entertaining by accident.

00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:49.800
If you're investing in something that costs anywhere from 200 million to 300 million dollars,

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:51.960
you aren't taking any chances.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:56.320
Every second of these films and TV shows is scrutinized by editors

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:59.160
and photographers and directors

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:03.540
and producers and marketing people and studio executives,

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:09.820
and it is designed to cater to our desires, to your desires to be as popular as possible

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:11.720
to as many people as possible.

00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:15.040
Hunter argues that what our biggest movies tell us is that

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:18.320
we're not interested in seeing reality as it is.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:22.260
We prefer worlds that are animated or in a galaxy far far away.

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:25.120
We prefer a universe populated with superheroes,

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:27.120
or an island populated by dinosaurs

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:30.820
or a super advanced kingdom hidden away in the jungle.

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:35.320
Now to be fair, popular entertainment has always had an escapist element,

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:38.520
though you could say that it's more prominent now than in the past.

00:01:38.520 --> 00:01:42.880
But what I find more interesting about Hunter's argument is a specific aversion

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:44.980
that he finds in the entertainment of today.

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:46.680
The resentment of our...

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:47.520
smartphones.

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:51.220
Those ever-present things that connect us to social media

00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:54.080
and capture more and more of our free time every year.

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:57.180
If we look at our most popular movies, he says,

00:01:57.180 --> 00:01:59.560
What we don't see, is our devices

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:02.360
I immediately became interested in the truth of this claim,

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:08.480
so I decided to take a closer look at the highest domestic grossing movies of this year, 2018

00:02:08.480 --> 00:02:09.995
to see if smartphones were in them,

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.380
and if they were, how exactly they were being used.

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:18.580
Okay, first in Black Panther, America's highest grossing movie in 2018 (and likely to stay that way),

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:21.755
There are three brief instances of smartphone use.

00:02:21.760 --> 00:02:25.340
First, by Linda. You guys remember Linda, right?

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:28.080
She uses her phone to intercept security footage.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:32.460
Then we see a couple shots of people taking pictures of T'Challa after a chase sequence

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:37.860
Then Claw uses one to text someone later in the film, though we don't see who or know why.

00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:43.500
In Avengers: Infinity War, there are exactly zero smartphones. None.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:47.660
However, Tony Stark, the most technologically advanced human on the planet,

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:50.440
who wears a suit made of nanoparticles,

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:52.560
does use a phone in the movie.

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:53.880
It just looks like this.

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:56.980
In the third highest grossing movie of 2018, The Incredibles 2,

00:02:56.980 --> 00:02:59.235
There are also zero smartphones,

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:04.200
having to do with the fact that the world has this mid-century, modern aesthetic

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:06.520
even though there are some high tech things...

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:07.520
it's confusing...

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:10.940
Like Infinity War however, there is no shortage of older phones.

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:13.420
In Jurrassic World: Fallen Kingdom,

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:18.720
We get our first look at a major character using a smartphone for something other than communication,

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:20.385
and we actually see what she's looking at

00:03:20.385 --> 00:03:22.940
Claire is reading the news.

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:28.000
though it's brief and the other three instances of smartphone use in this movie are all phone calls.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.140
In Deadpool 2, we get one phone call,

00:03:30.140 --> 00:03:33.180
one mindless surf from Yukio,

