(I couldn't get access to 9 and 10 because they're still out in theatres,

00:04:14.060 --> 00:04:15.440
but I think this is a good sample.

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:17.840
The uses breakdown like this:

00:04:17.840 --> 00:04:20.700
Five phone calls, two video calls,

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:24.000
four what I'll call single-use spy stuff

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:28.040
one news source, two camera, two unknown, Claw and Yukio,

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:30.700
and one "Say Anything" homage.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:33.140
If we're trying to determine the truth of Professor Hunter's claim,

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:37.460
that the lack of smartphones is indicative of a popular resentment

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:41.500
toward the way these devices control our lives and eat up our free time,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:45.035
we should compare the way that people use smartphones in these movies

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:46.860
to the way that we do.

00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:52.900
Through that lens, we can see that at least five of these uses have little or no relationship to real life,

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:54.720
unless you're a spy, that is.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:59.620
Phone calls, similarly, are an activity that can just as easily be done on Tony Stark's flip phone

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:01.460
or Mr. Incredible's cordless.

00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:03.500
That leaves only six uses:

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:08.000
video calls are I don't think something that most of us worry about when it comes to time wasting,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.580
same for taking photos.

00:05:09.580 --> 00:05:13.300
And as for Yukio and Claw, we don't even see what they're doing.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:17.020
That leaves this single instance of Claire checking the news.

00:05:17.020 --> 00:05:18.840
Now, for me at least,

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:22.740
that is definitely a common time-sucking use of my smartphone.

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:26.340
In the end, you can decide for  yourself whether this evidence is conclusive.

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:30.760
I think there is enough here to at least partially support Hunter's claims,

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:33.900
because though there are smartphones in some of these movies,

00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:37.820
their combined runtime comes out to only about a minute, if that,

00:05:37.820 --> 00:05:42.440
and I don't think we really see anyone using them in the ways we might be frustrated with

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:47.820
in our, on average, 3.3 hours of mobile usage a day.

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:49.640
And I'm more convinced when I realize that

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:51.180
in all of these films,

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:55.200
there are no references or mentions at all of social media.

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:57.060
According to the data company "Apptopia",

00:05:57.060 --> 00:06:03.400
across the hundred most popular apps, 54% of screen time is spent in apps owned by Google or Facebook.

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:07.980
That's things like Youtube, Gmail, Facebook, WhatsApp, and Instagram.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:10.995
None of these apps, or any generic equivalents,

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.960
appear in the highest grossing movies of 2018.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:17.740
The time-wasting, data-mining, addiction-creating activity

00:06:17.740 --> 00:06:23.640
that has become a key, maybe even a defining feature, of our relationship with these devices

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:26.340
is absent from our most popular entertainment.

00:06:26.340 --> 00:06:30.640
Now this doesn't mean that our smartphones and social media don't feature in any movies.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:34.540
In fact, one of the best movies of this year in my opinion, Bo Burnham's "Eighth Grade",

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:39.320
is all about the ways that our devices and the social internet shape the way we interact.

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:44.080
Confronting that relationship is, and will be, an important subject for film.

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:49.520
But our most popular movies have never really been about confronting our fears and resentments,

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:51.520
They're about escaping them

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:54.420
for about a couple hours at the end of a hard week,

00:06:54.540 --> 00:07:00.420
and in that spirit, I think you can say that smartphones may play a big role in our lives,

00:07:00.420 --> 00:07:02.640
bigger maybe than we want to admit,

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:06.540
but they barely have any part in our biggest movies.

